MRC Centre for Global Infectious Disease Analysis, Imperial College London

Imperial College COVID-19 LMIC Reports

Forecasting the healthcare burden of COVID-19 in LMICs


COVID-19 has caused large-scale outbreaks in many countries, particularly in Europe and Asia where many countries have experienced a level of healthcare demand that have placed health systems under strain. Many countries, particularly Low- or Middle Income countries (LMICs) (shown below), are at an earlier stage of the epidemic. 126 countries have reported less than 100 COVID-19 deaths, with 87 where the total COVID-19 deaths also represents less than 10/million of their population.

In response, we provide daily updated forecasts for LMICs, helping to provide them with an indication of where they are in their epidemic. Specifically, these reports will aim to help countries understand:


1. The total number of COVID-19 infections

2. The expected number of deaths within the next 28 days

3. The number of individuals requiring oxygen or mechanical ventilation in the next 28 days

4. The impact of changing their current intervention policy


For further guidance and questions about the methodology and caveats, please see the Frequently Asked Questions


Cumulative Deaths since 10 deaths by continent for low- and middle-income countries. The projected deaths (assuming population mobility is maintained at today’s level) are shown with dashed lines.

METHODOLOGY

As in our projections for high-income settings at more advanced stages of the epidemic, rather than relying upon reported cases which are likely to be subject to a high and varying degree of under reporting, we use reported deaths as a more reliable indicator of disease spread. These data are then used to back-calculate an ‘inferred number of COVID-19 infections’ that we estimate have occurred within each country up to the current day, adjusted for the demographics and representative patterns of social mixing within each country.

Using data on the age-dependent risk of requiring hospitalisation, oxygen and mechanical ventilation by age observed in other countries to date, we use our model to project forwards the likely demand for healthcare over the coming four weeks. This data is currently from high-income countries and consequently likely under estimates the true burden. Full methods used, with parameter values can be found in the Methods Section.

These reports are updated daily using the latest publicly available data on COVID-19 from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control. We also model the impact of government interventions that have been put in place and their effect on human mobility based on the Google COVID-19 Community Mobility Reports.
